#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:10
msgid "Build Caches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:12
msgid ""
"Some sites may encourage users to set up their own test environments before "
"carrying out central installations, or some users may prefer to set up these "
"environments on their own motivation. To reduce the load of recompiling "
"otherwise identical package specs in different installations, installed "
"packages can be put into build cache tarballs, pushed to your Spack mirror "
"and then downloaded and installed by others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:19
msgid ""
"Whenever a mirror provides prebuilt packages, Spack will take these packages "
"into account during concretization and installation, making ``spack "
"install`` significantly faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:26
msgid ""
"We use the terms \"build cache\" and \"mirror\" often interchangeably. "
"Mirrors are used during installation both for sources and prebuilt packages. "
"Build caches refer to mirrors that provide prebuilt packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:33
msgid "Creating a build cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:35
msgid "Build caches are created via:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:37
msgid "$ spack buildcache push <path/url/mirror name> <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:41
msgid ""
"This command takes the locally installed spec and its dependencies, and "
"creates tarballs of their install prefixes. It also generates metadata "
"files, signed with GPG. These tarballs and metadata files are then pushed to "
"the provided binary cache, which can be a local directory or a remote URL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:46
msgid ""
"Here is an example where a build cache is created in a local directory named "
"\"spack-cache\", to which we push the \"ninja\" spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:49
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache push ./spack-cache ninja\n"
"==> Pushing binary packages to file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache/"
"build_cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:54
msgid "Note that ``ninja`` must be installed locally for this to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:56
msgid ""
"Once you have a build cache, you can add it as a mirror, discussed next."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:60
msgid "Finding or installing build cache files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:62
msgid ""
"To find build caches or install build caches, a Spack mirror must be "
"configured with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:65
msgid "$ spack mirror add <name> <url or path>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:70
msgid ""
"Both web URLs and local paths on the filesystem can be specified. In the "
"previous example, you might add the directory \"spack-cache\" and call it "
"``mymirror``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:74
msgid "$ spack mirror add mymirror ./spack-cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:79
msgid ""
"You can see that the mirror is added with ``spack mirror list`` as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:81
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror list\n"
"mymirror           file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache\n"
"spack-public       https://spack-llnl-mirror.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:89
msgid ""
"At this point, you've create a buildcache, but spack hasn't indexed it, so "
"if you run ``spack buildcache list`` you won't see any results. You need to "
"index this new build cache as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:93
msgid "$ spack buildcache update-index ./spack-cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:97
msgid "Now you can use list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:99
msgid ""
"$  spack buildcache list\n"
"==> 1 cached build.\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu20.04-skylake / gcc@9.3.0 ------------------------\n"
"ninja@1.10.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:106
msgid ""
"With ``mymirror`` configured and an index available, Spack will "
"automatically use it during concretization and installation. That means that "
"you can expect ``spack install ninja`` to fetch prebuilt packages from the "
"mirror. Let's verify by re-installing ninja:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:111
msgid ""
"$ spack uninstall ninja\n"
"$ spack install ninja\n"
"==> Installing ninja-1.11.1-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz\n"
"==> Fetching file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache/build_cache/linux-"
"ubuntu20.04-skylake-gcc-9.3.0-ninja-1.10.2-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz."
"spec.json.sig\n"
"gpg: Signature made Do 12 Jan 2023 16:01:04 CET\n"
"gpg:                using RSA key 61B82B2B2350E171BD17A1744E3A689061D57BF6\n"
"gpg: Good signature from \"example (GPG created for Spack) <example@example."
"com>\" [ultimate]\n"
"==> Fetching file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache/build_cache/linux-"
"ubuntu20.04-skylake/gcc-9.3.0/ninja-1.10.2/linux-ubuntu20.04-skylake-"
"gcc-9.3.0-ninja-1.10.2-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz.spack\n"
"==> Extracting ninja-1.10.2-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz from binary "
"cache\n"
"==> ninja: Successfully installed ninja-1.11.1-"
"yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz\n"
"Search: 0.00s.  Fetch: 0.17s.  Install: 0.12s.  Total: 0.29s\n"
"[+] /home/harmen/spack/opt/spack/linux-ubuntu20.04-skylake/gcc-9.3.0/"
"ninja-1.11.1-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:127
msgid ""
"It worked! You've just completed a full example of creating a build cache "
"with a spec of interest, adding it as a mirror, updating its index, listing "
"the contents, and finally, installing from it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:131
msgid ""
"By default Spack falls back to building from sources when the mirror is not "
"available or when the package is simply not already available. To force "
"Spack to only install prebuilt packages, you can use"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:135
msgid "$ spack install --use-buildcache only <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:139
msgid ""
"For example, to combine all of the commands above to add the E4S build cache "
"and then install from it exclusively, you would do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:142
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add E4S https://cache.e4s.io\n"
"$ spack buildcache keys --install --trust\n"
"$ spack install --use-buildcache only <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:148
msgid ""
"We use ``--install`` and ``--trust`` to say that we are installing keys to "
"our keyring, and trusting all downloaded keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:154
msgid "List of popular build caches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:156
msgid ""
"`Extreme-scale Scientific Software Stack (E4S) <https://e4s-project.github."
"io/>`_: `build cache <https://oaciss.uoregon.edu/e4s/inventory.html>`_'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:160
msgid "Build cache signing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:162
msgid ""
"By default, Spack will add a cryptographic signature to each package pushed "
"to a build cache, and verifies the signature when installing from a build "
"cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:165
msgid ""
"Keys for signing can be managed with the :ref:`spack gpg <cmd-spack-gpg>` "
"command, as well as ``spack buildcache keys`` as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:168
msgid ""
"You can disable signing when pushing with ``spack buildcache push --"
"unsigned``, and disable verification when installing from any build cache "
"with ``spack install --no-check-signature``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:172
msgid ""
"Alternatively, signing and verification can be enabled or disabled on a per "
"build cache basis:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:175
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add --signed <name> <url>  # enable signing and verification\n"
"$ spack mirror add --unsigned <name> <url>  # disable signing and "
"verification\n"
"\n"
"$ spack mirror set --signed <name>  # enable signing and verification for an "
"existing mirror\n"
"$ spack mirror set --unsigned <name>  # disable signing and verification for "
"an existing mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:183
msgid "Or you can directly edit the ``mirrors.yaml`` configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:185
msgid ""
"mirrors:\n"
"  <name>:\n"
"    url: <url>\n"
"    signed: false # disable signing and verification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:192
msgid "See also :ref:`mirrors`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:196
msgid "Relocation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:198
msgid ""
"When using buildcaches across different machines, it is likely that the "
"install root will be different from the one used to build the binaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:201
msgid ""
"To address this issue, Spack automatically relocates all paths encoded in "
"binaries and scripts to their new location upon install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:204
msgid ""
"Note that there are some cases where this is not possible: if binaries are "
"built in a relatively short path, and then installed to a longer path, there "
"may not be enough space in the binary to encode the new path. In this case, "
"Spack will fail to install the package from the build cache, and a source "
"build is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:209
msgid ""
"To reduce the likelihood of this happening, it is highly recommended to add "
"padding to the install root during the build, as specified in the :ref:"
"`config <config-yaml>` section of the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:213
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /opt/spack\n"
"    padded_length: 128"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:225
msgid "Automatic push to a build cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:227
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is convenient to push packages to a build cache as soon as they "
"are installed. Spack can do this by setting autopush flag when adding a "
"mirror:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:229
msgid "$ spack mirror add --autopush <name> <url or path>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:233
msgid "Or the autopush flag can be set for an existing mirror:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:235
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror set --autopush <name>  # enable automatic push for an "
"existing mirror\n"
"$ spack mirror set --no-autopush <name>  # disable automatic push for an "
"existing mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:240
msgid ""
"Then after installing a package it is automatically pushed to all mirrors "
"with ``autopush: true``. The command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:242
msgid "$ spack install <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:246
msgid "will have the same effect as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:248
msgid ""
"$ spack install <package>\n"
"$ spack buildcache push <cache> <package>  # for all caches with autopush: "
"true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:255
msgid ""
"Packages are automatically pushed to a build cache only if they are built "
"from source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:259
msgid "OCI / Docker V2 registries as build cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:261
msgid ""
"Spack can also use OCI or Docker V2 registries such as Dockerhub, Quay.io, "
"Github Packages, GitLab Container Registry, JFrog Artifactory, and others as "
"build caches. This is a convenient way to share binaries using public "
"infrastructure, or to cache Spack built binaries in Github Actions and "
"GitLab CI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:267
msgid ""
"To get started, configure an OCI mirror using ``oci://`` as the scheme, and "
"optionally specify variables that hold the username and password (or "
"personal access token) for the registry:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:271
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add --oci-username-variable REGISTRY_USER \\\n"
"                   --oci-password-variable REGISTRY_TOKEN \\\n"
"                   my_registry oci://example.com/my_image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:277
msgid ""
"Spack follows the naming conventions of Docker, with Dockerhub as the "
"default registry. To use Dockerhub, you can omit the registry domain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:280
msgid "$ spack mirror add ... my_registry oci://username/my_image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:284
msgid "From here, you can use the mirror as any other build cache:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:286
msgid ""
"$ export REGISTRY_USER=...\n"
"$ export REGISTRY_TOKEN=...\n"
"$ spack buildcache push my_registry <specs...>  # push to the registry\n"
"$ spack install <specs...>  # or install from the registry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:293
msgid ""
"A unique feature of buildcaches on top of OCI registries is that it's "
"incredibly easy to generate get a runnable container image with the binaries "
"installed. This is a great way to make applications available to users "
"without requiring them to install Spack -- all you need is Docker, Podman or "
"any other OCI-compatible container runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:299
msgid ""
"To produce container images, all you need to do is add the ``--base-image`` "
"flag when pushing to the build cache:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:302
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache push --base-image ubuntu:20.04 my_registry ninja\n"
"Pushed to example.com/my_image:ninja-1.11.1-yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz."
"spack\n"
"\n"
"$ docker run -it example.com/my_image:ninja-1.11.1-"
"yxferyhmrjkosgta5ei6b4lqf6bxbscz.spack\n"
"root@e4c2b6f6b3f4:/# ninja --version\n"
"1.11.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:311
msgid ""
"If ``--base-image`` is not specified, distroless images are produced. In "
"practice, you won't be able to run these as containers, since they don't "
"come with libc and other system dependencies. However, they are still "
"compatible with tools like ``skopeo``, ``podman``, and ``docker`` for "
"pulling and pushing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:317
msgid ""
"The docker ``overlayfs2`` storage driver is limited to 128 layers, above "
"which a ``max depth exceeded`` error may be produced when pulling the image. "
"There are `alternative drivers <https://docs.docker.com/storage/"
"storagedriver/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:323
msgid "Spack build cache for GitHub Actions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:325
msgid ""
"To significantly speed up Spack in GitHub Actions, binaries can be cached in "
"GitHub Packages. This service is an OCI registry that can be linked to a "
"GitHub repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:329
msgid ""
"Spack offers a public build cache for GitHub Actions with a set of common "
"packages, which lets you get started quickly. See the following resources "
"for more information:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:332
msgid ""
"`spack/setup-spack <https://github.com/spack/setup-spack>`_ for setting up "
"Spack in GitHub Actions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:334
msgid ""
"`spack/github-actions-buildcache <https://github.com/spack/github-actions-"
"buildcache>`_ for more details on the public build cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:341
msgid "``spack buildcache``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:345
msgid "``spack buildcache push``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:347
msgid ""
"Create tarball of installed Spack package and all dependencies. Tarballs are "
"checksummed and signed if gpg2 is available. Places them in a directory "
"``build_cache`` that can be copied to a mirror. Commands like ``spack "
"buildcache install`` will search Spack mirrors for build_cache to get the "
"list of build caches."
msgstr ""

